                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/07/2003&nbsp;: 11:45:33 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> In regards to making a sig with an illegal version of Adobe, my whole point is that I, personally, wouldn't come down hard on that.  What happens in regards to the law is another matter.<br /><br />And I don't think that this area is as grey as you make it out to be.  It's pretty generally accepted that if you go 5 over, you're okay.  If you go 10 over, you're probably getting a ticket unless everyone around you is doing 15+.  The grey area is pretty narrow.<br /><br />(I *legally* own Adobe, so I don't have to make these distinctions.  However, were it me, I would just make my sig with another program.)<br /><br />Piracy is wrong.  Just as you said, it hurts the little guys.  It kills them when people do it with movies.  Piracy almost tanked the Hong Kong film industry.<br /><br />My entire point = Stop Pirating Things<br /><br />Oh and btw, you mentioned movies as complaining about piracy and also being the ones that make the most money.  Movies also cost *a lot* more to make than music or software.  If piracy gets out of hand on the movie front, a hell of a lot of movies that would get made, never will.  Piracy kills movies.</span></font></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Abillister_Abu</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;08/07/2003&nbsp;: 03:25:37 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> right but you also said it was ok for someone to download adobe so they could make a sig, and then i'm assuming you were implying they would delete it.  but that is no less illegal then downloading an entire music album to see how it is...deciding the CD isn't worth buying, but to keep a song or two that you like.<br /><br />there is a difference between 5 and 35, but where do you draw the line?  is 10 still not that bad because it isn't 35?  there in lies the problem, each person has their own distinction of where the line is at (assuming they see a line at all).  if you notice, i'm not arguing that it isn't morally wrong and shouldn't be done...i'm just pointing out the reality of it.  personally, i'm the type of person that doesn't even like to go movie hopping (though as i've gotten older and a better sense of money, i'm much more likely to do it then i was back when my parents paid for everything...i don't have the money to pay for every movie i want to see in the theatres...a tip for any youngins, stay under your parents wing as long as you can.  i have friends that wanted to be on their own and pay for everything, even though their parents could afford to support them, and they need to work full time to support themselves.  it is foolish to not accept what is offered, when you know the ones offering it CAN offer it).<br /><br />it is kind of like that cop that goes 90+ in a 65 or 70, they know the chance of them getting in trouble are slim to none, so they fly down the road breaking the very laws they enforce (though that is a different topic); in comparison with stopping other crimes (murders, robbers, etc...) their speeding is somewhat accepted because of this.  in comparison with stealing a $100,000 or even a $10,000 car people see 'stealing' software/music by downloading it as acceptable.<br /><br />should it be? no.  doesn't change the fact of the matter.<br /><br />it is kind of funny; the most feared police in florida (by other law enforcement...at least that is what i was told by an FBI agent) are the sheriffs and highway patrol because both of those people will ticket other officers (and federal agents)...yet the ones you see speeding more then any other, are those very ones.<br />--------<br /><br />This kind of has little to do with the if it should or shouldn't be done...more of just something i wanted to mention because i appreciated the work these people do.<br />have you ever downloaded any of the Anime Music Videos?  they are VERY well done videos that you can tell a lot of time, effort, and skill were put into.  but having known people that used to (they actually still might, haven't talked to them in a while) do those, i know they used pirated software.  there is no way they could've ever afforded the software to do that...and they make these great videos for free, and distribute them for free.  there are even groups now that can be FOUND that make these videos: the images used in these videos are all ripped without permission from anime shows.  yet despite the fact that these people could easily be tracked down and sued, i've not heard of a single case in which this has happened.<br /><br />something interesting...if you notice, it is the movie and music industries (the ones that make the MOST money...and yes i know who it is that loses money; the behind the scene people not the actors/company) that are complaining the most about this issue.  the software industries aren't making nearly as big of a deal, and they can track down pirated software 100 times easier then one could movies/music.</span></font></td>
